<p>Newer developments like Brookhaven, Westwood, and the neighborhoods around Lake Thunderbird typically feature homes with better solar orientation and fewer shading obstacles. These areas, with homes built in the 1980s and later, often have adequate electrical panels and structural support for solar installations. The newer subdivisions east of I-35, including areas like Alameda and Sheffield, offer excellent solar potential with minimal shading and modern electrical infrastructure. Rural areas in Cleveland County outside Norman proper may have additional considerations for solar installations, including potential requirements for ground-mounted systems and considerations for longer utility connection runs.</p>

